## Discussion and Conclusion

This paper started by acknowledging the premise that patenting activities can be considered as a proxy for innovation processes. These activities combine exiting technologies in different configuration to generate new knowledge. We extended this premise by arguing that the combinatorial constraints of existing knowledge can be bridged through collaboration which increases the knowledge pool. We hypothesised that collaboration moderate the influence of patent's portfolio characteristics on its technological and commercial value. Our results confirmed this hypothesis and revealed that this relationship is contingent on the collaboration context, though technological value (citations) and commercial value (renewals) respond through different mechanisms. Our findings provide a different approach to assessing patent value by considering the endogenous characteristics of the technologies for each patent. These results can guide policy makers to design instruments that capitalise on the strengths and weaknesses of innovation ecosystems at regional, national, and European levels.   

Our contribution in this paper is two folds. Empirically, we confirm our initial hypothesis that the collaboration patterns moderate the influence of technology characteristics on patent value and we show that this moderation is different for commercial and technological value. Whereas methodologically, we rely on an adaptation of the feature importance product space approach to estimate the bi-directional and asymmetric relationships between technologies to avoid the issues arising from co-occurrence and co-citations approaches. 

The results reported in this paper show that regional collaboration rewards enabler technologies and network reachability for citations, but commercial value is influenced only by enabler technologies with domain specialization, not integrative platforms or cross-domain connections—consistent with findings in [@gao2023knowledge; @qiu2017emerging] that local knowledge is most valuable for locally-rooted technologies. This pattern also reflects the observation in [@sonmez2018interregional] that organisational collaboration produces more economically valuable inventions when collaborating inventors are co-located, and that technologically similar inter-industry knowledge flows create greater economic value. Similarly, the results in  [@breschi2004knowledge] show that inventors linked by shorter social chains cite each other more explains why network reachability matters for technological recognition in regional contexts where social distance is minimal unlike the national and international collaboration contexts.

On the other hand, national collaboration extends this pattern: integrative technologies and domain specialists gain recognition, yet commercial value accrues only to enabler technologies with connection evenness. This aligns with [@singh2013geographic], where the authors observed that national borders constrain knowledge diffusion. [@sonmez2018interregional]  finds that interregional collaboration leads to more valuable patents when inventors share organizational affiliation. Which suggests that the citation premium for integrative technologies may reflect the output of ongoing ambitious projects unrelated to commercialisation objectives. 


Finally, international collaboration shows the most contrasting patterns: technological value strongly rewards integrative, domain-specialized, and cross-domain connected technologies, while commercial value depends almost exclusively on connection evenness, with bridging technologies penalized in both dimensions aligning with similar findings in [@qiu2017emerging; @wan2019dynamics]. Moreover, the results in [@ascani2020global] shows that regional specialization and global networks work synergistically, aligns with our results and explains why international collaboration rewards both domain specialization and cross-domain connections for recognition, yet commercial value requires the stable connection patterns that enable actual knowledge integration. 

While our approach offers important insights into the innovation ecosystem of European regions from a technology network perspective, several caveats are worth noting. First, our framework builds on machine learning–based relatedness modeling [@tacchella2023relatedness; @fessina2024identifying]. These methods originally capture relatedness through observed flows between products, whereas technology networks rely on co-occurrence and are not organically linked. Even patent citation networks are partly constructed, since they depend on examiner decisions [@hegde2009examiner]. Our methodological contribution builds on  [@breschi2004knowledge] assessment that knowledge flows follow a complex social chains that networks analysis and metrics are adequate to capture. Our adaptation of the FIPS approach extends this idea by leveraging asymmetric nature of the network we constructed.  
Additionally, unlike the original formulation, we omitted the statistical validation step for the feature importance for each model due to computational burden.  We justify our decision here by the results reported by [@fessina2024identifying] and [@albora2023product] where even with the default parameters, random forest is a better predictor of these relationships than RCA is. However, future work could address this issue using the approach in [@saracco2015randomizing]. Second, our econometric analysis relied on aggregated metrics at the patent level. While convenient, this weighted mean aggregation likely obscures some granular information. Structural equation modeling was not feasible given the complexity of our zero-inflated negative binomial framework, but a promising alternative would be to construct priors for the aggregated variables and pursue a Bayesian approach under similar assumptions.










